07080nam a22012735i 9783839414477DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20152010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1010505675  a97838394144777 a10.1515/transcript.97838394144772doi  a(DE-B1597)453057  a(OCoLC)932043674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a177/.700aCare in Practice :bOn Tinkering in Clinics, Homes and Farms /ced. by Jeannette Pols, Ingunn Moser, Annemarie Mol.  a1. Aufl. 1aBielefeld : btranscript Verlag, c[2015] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVerKörperungen/MatteRealities - Perspektiven empirischer Wissenschaftsforschung ;v800tFrontmatter -- tEditorial -- tContents -- tCare: putting practice into theory -- tOn recognition, caring, and dementia -- tCare and killing Tensions in veterinary practice -- tHow to become a guardian angel Providing safety in a home telecare service -- tCare and disability Practices of experimenting, tinkering with, and arranging people and technical aids -- tNow or later? Individual disease and care collectives in the memory clinic -- tAnimal farm love stories About care and economy Telecare What patients care about -- tWhen patients care (too much) for information -- tCare and its values Good food in the nursing home -- tGood farming Control or care? -- tVarieties of goodness in high-tech home care -- tPerhaps tears should not be counted but wiped away On quality and improvement in dementia care -- tThe syndrome we care for XPERIMENT! -- tList of authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn what way is »care« a matter of »tinkering«? Rather than presenting care as a (preferably »warm«) relation between human beings, the various contributions to the volume give the material world (usually cast as »cold«) a prominent place in their analysis. Thus, this book does not continue to oppose care and technology, but contributes to rethinking both in such a way that they can be analysed together.Technology is not cast as a functional tool, easy to control - it is shifting, changing, surprising and adaptable. In care practices all »things« are (and have to be) tinkered with persistently. Knowledge is fluid, too. Rather than a set of general rules, the knowledges (in the plural) relevant to care practices are as adaptable and in need of adaptation as the technologies, the bodies, the people, and the daily lives involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCaring. 0aEthics. 0aHumanitarianism. 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 4aBioethics. 4aBody. 4aCare Ethics. 4aClinical Practice. 4aDisabilities. 4aFarming. 4aHealth Care. 4aHome Care. 4aMedical Ethics. 4aMedicine. 4aSociology. 4aTechnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBioethics.  aBody.  aCare Ethics.  aClinical Practice.  aDisabilities.  aFarming.  aHealth Care.  aHome Care.  aMedical Ethics.  aMedicine.  aSociology.  aTechnology.1 aCallén, Blanca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomènech, Miquel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbers, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraeftner, Bernd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroell, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangstrup, Henriette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMol, Annemarie, econtributor.